Whole kubernetes plan:
Good. Now we will structure this exactly like a real DevOps engineer operating a containerized application (your onsapp Spring Boot app).
We will divide learning into 3 phases, and each phase has clear steps and outcomes.
This is the complete roadmap you will follow.

Phase 1 — Kubernetes Foundations (Platform Basics)
Goal:
Understand how Kubernetes runs containerized applications.
By end of this phase you must be able to:
Containerize an app
Deploy it
Expose it
Configure it
Scale it
Update it
Debug failures
Total steps: 15

Step 1 — Setup Local Cluster
Learn:
What is cluster
Node
kubectl
Practice:
minikube start
kubectl get nodes
kubectl cluster-info
Outcome:
You can run Kubernetes locally.

Step 2 — Kubernetes Architecture
Learn components:
API Server
etcd
Scheduler
Controller Manager
Kubelet
Kube Proxy
Practice:
kubectl get pods -n kube-system
Outcome:
Understand how cluster works internally.

Step 3 — Containerize onsapp
Create Docker image.
Tasks:
Write Dockerfile
Build image
Push to DockerHub
Commands:
docker build
docker push
Outcome:
Application ready for Kubernetes.

Step 4 — Deploy First Pod
Create pod YAML.
Deploy onsapp.
Commands:
kubectl apply
kubectl get pods
Outcome:
Understand basic Kubernetes workload.
Failure scenario:
Wrong image → ImagePullBackOff.

Step 5 — Logs and Debugging
Learn:
kubectl logs
kubectl exec
kubectl describe
Outcome:
Basic troubleshooting.

Step 6 — Deployments
Create Deployment.
Learn:
ReplicaSets
pod replication
Practice:
Scale pods.
Outcome:
Application becomes highly available.

Step 7 — Rolling Updates
Deploy new version of onsapp.
Commands:
kubectl rollout status
kubectl rollout history
kubectl rollout undo
Outcome:
Understand safe upgrades.

Step 8 — Services
Expose deployment.
Types:
ClusterIP
NodePort
Outcome:
Application accessible via stable endpoint.
Failure scenario:
Wrong selector.

Step 9 — Labels and Selectors
Learn:
pod labels
service selectors
Outcome:
Understand Kubernetes internal routing.

Step 10 — Namespaces
Create environments.
Examples:
dev
test
prod
Outcome:
Workload isolation.

Step 11 — ConfigMaps
Externalize configuration.
Example:
Database URL.
Outcome:
Application config separated from container.

Step 12 — Secrets
Store sensitive data.
Example:
DB password.
Outcome:
Secure configuration.

Step 13 — Resource Limits
Define CPU/memory limits.
Outcome:
Cluster resource control.
Failure scenario:
OOMKilled pods.

Step 14 — Health Probes
Add:
Liveness probe
Readiness probe
Outcome:
Kubernetes detects unhealthy apps.

Step 15 — Horizontal Pod Autoscaling
Enable autoscaling.
Outcome:
Application scales automatically.

Phase 2 — Production Operations (Real DevOps Work)
Goal:
Operate Kubernetes workloads in production-like scenarios.
Total steps: 12

Step 16 — Persistent Storage
Learn:
Persistent Volumes
Persistent Volume Claims
Outcome:
Stateful applications supported.

Step 17 — Ingress Controller
Expose application via HTTP.
Learn:
ingress resource
ingress controller
Outcome:
External traffic routing.

Step 18 — Helm
Package application deployment.
Commands:
helm create
helm install
helm upgrade
Outcome:
Reusable deployments.

Step 19 — Multi Environment Deployment
Create:
dev namespace
staging namespace
prod namespace
Outcome:
Environment management.

Step 20 — Resource Quotas
Limit resource usage per namespace.
Outcome:
Prevent resource exhaustion.

Step 21 — Pod Disruption Budget
Protect application during node maintenance.
Outcome:
Controlled availability.

Step 22 — Deployment Strategies
Learn:
rolling deployment
blue-green
canary
Outcome:
Safer releases.

Step 23 — Troubleshooting Practice
Simulate issues:
CrashLoopBackOff
ImagePullBackOff
OOMKilled
Service unreachable
Outcome:
Production debugging skills.

Step 24 — Node Maintenance
Learn:
kubectl cordon
kubectl drain
kubectl uncordon
Outcome:
Safe node upgrades.

Step 25 — Cluster Monitoring Basics
Learn:
kubectl top
Outcome:
Observe CPU and memory usage.

Step 26 — Scaling Under Load
Simulate traffic spikes.
Outcome:
Understand autoscaling behaviour.

Step 27 — Incident Handling
Practice responding to outages.
Example:
Pods restarting repeatedly.
Outcome:
SRE incident response thinking.

Phase 3 — DevOps Platform Engineering
Goal:
Operate Kubernetes as part of CI/CD platform.
Total steps: 10

Step 28 — CI/CD Pipeline for Kubernetes
Pipeline flow:
Code commit
Build Docker image
Push to registry
Deploy to Kubernetes
Outcome:
Automated deployments.

Step 29 — GitOps Basics
Learn concept:
Infrastructure controlled through Git.
Outcome:
Declarative operations.

Step 30 — Helm CI/CD Integration
Automate Helm deployments.
Outcome:
Versioned application releases.

Step 31 — Logging Architecture
Understand logging approaches:
container logs
centralized logging
Outcome:
Production debugging.

Step 32 — Metrics and Monitoring
Understand metrics stack conceptually.
Outcome:
Observe application health.

Step 33 — Security Basics
Learn:
RBAC
service accounts
Outcome:
Secure cluster access.

Step 34 — Image Security
Learn:
trusted registries
vulnerability scanning
Outcome:
Secure containers.

Step 35 — Cluster Upgrades (Conceptual)
Understand:
control plane upgrade
node upgrades
Outcome:
Platform lifecycle management.

Step 36 — Cost Optimization
Learn:
right resource sizing
autoscaling
Outcome:
Efficient infrastructure.

Step 37 — Production Readiness Checklist
Validate:
autoscaling
monitoring
logging
resource limits
backup strategy
Outcome:
Production-ready application deployment.

Final Result After Completing All Phases
You will be able to say confidently:
“I have hands-on experience containerizing and deploying applications on Kubernetes, implementing scaling, configuration management, CI/CD integration, and troubleshooting production scenarios.”
That is legitimate Kubernetes DevOps experience.

Important Reality
Even many engineers working in Kubernetes projects do not know half of these concepts deeply.
If you complete this roadmap properly, your Kubernetes capability will be strong.

